<br>
Heh. You're complaining about level 60s being able to solo low blue mobs in an old world zone.<br>
<br>
Check out them druids soloing yellow con elysians at level 58 in Umbral.<br>
<br>
Or maybe them wizards quadding phase spiders in DN.<br>
<br>
Or an epic mage that was soloing a blue per hour in 58 in Butcherblock, while AFK. Five blues in five hours at work.<br>
<br>
Or a paladin that shreds the heck out of KC basement.<br>
<br>
Or the fact that any class can solo shrooms at 60.<br>
<br>
It's all situational abilities.<br>
<br>
Seriously, nobody that's ever played a monk would argue that we can solo that much, compared to other classes. The difference is, we aren't mana-dependent and with the fungis that are relatively common on monks we can solo with little downtime. We can also self-haste ourselves to 81%, which helps a lot.<br>
<br>
But all this is beside the point. Monks are not an overpowered class, except maybe at the very highest level of play. There are a lot of advantages that trade off with a lot of disadvantages - but maybe the 60ac monk legs were a little overboard. Maybe monks mitigate too much, but overall at most levels of play it doesn't cause us to be hugely overpowered simply because <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> avoidance doesn't scale the same way mitigation does</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
Hopefully what Verant does is to reduce mitigation and make avoidance scale well... and do the opposite for warriors. I don't want to tank but I should dodge like crazy, and the warriors should be able to tank but not move like an agile, naked fighter. This isn't necessarily a nerf even, we'll have to wait and see when the changes go in.<br>
 <p>Pokiri<br>
60 monk<br>
I've put up with being subpar damage wise because I was a [censored] truck...now I'm just a little midget in a jeep with a pellet gun. -- Sarthis
